{
  "id": "freefall-drag",
  "title": "Falling with air resistance",
  "topic": "freefall",
  "slug": "terminal-velocity",
  "scenario": "An object is dropped from rest and feels air resistance proportional to its speed (m = 1 kg, drag b = 0.5 kg/s). Does it keep speeding up forever — and why can't the algebra formulas answer that?",
  "regime": 2,
  "constants": {
    "m": 1.0,
    "b": 0.5,
    "g": -10.0
  },
  "initial_conditions": {
    "x0": 0.0,
    "v0": 0.0
  },
  "assumptions": [
    {
      "claim": "Air resistance is linear in speed (drag = -b·v). Real drag is often closer to quadratic; the linear model keeps the closed form clean.",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "g = -10 m/s^2, a clean-arithmetic simplification of -9.81 m/s^2.",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "The object is a point mass.",
      "kind": "model"
    }
  ],
  "algebra": {
    "steps": [
      {
        "label": "Where the algebra-based course stops",
        "latex": "x = x_0 + v_0 t + \\tfrac{1}{2}a t^2 \\;\\; \\text{(does NOT apply: } a \\text{ is not constant)}",
        "prose": "With air resistance the acceleration changes as the object speeds up, so the constant-a formulas fail. At best you're handed the terminal velocity v = mg/b as a fact, with no path to it."
      }
    ],
    "result": {
      "terminal_velocity": {
        "label": "Terminal velocity $mg/b$",
        "unit": "m/s",
        "symbolic_latex": "g \\tau",
        "value": -20.0,
        "display": "-20"
      },
      "time_constant": {
        "label": "Time constant $\\tau = m/b$",
        "unit": "s",
        "symbolic_latex": "\\tau",
        "value": 2.0,
        "display": "2"
      }
    }
  },
  "calculus": {
    "steps": [
      {
        "label": "Newton's second law with linear drag",
        "latex": "m\\,v' = mg - b\\,v \\;\\;\\Longrightarrow\\;\\; v' = g - \\tfrac{v}{\\tau},\\quad \\tau = \\tfrac{m}{b}",
        "prose": "Drag opposes motion and grows with speed, so the net force — and the acceleration — shrink as the object speeds up. This is a differential equation, not algebra."
      },
      {
        "label": "Solve the linear ODE",
        "latex": "v(t) = v_{\\text{term}} + (v_0 - v_{\\text{term}})\\,e^{-t/\\tau},\\quad v_{\\text{term}} = g\\tau = \\tfrac{mg}{b}",
        "prose": "Velocity approaches the terminal value exponentially, with time constant τ."
      },
      {
        "label": "Acceleration decays to zero",
        "latex": "a(t) = \\frac{v_{\\text{term}} - v_0}{\\tau}\\,e^{-t/\\tau} \\;\\to\\; 0",
        "prose": "Unlike free fall (where a is constant), here the acceleration decays: drag grows until it cancels gravity and there is no net force."
      },
      {
        "label": "Terminal velocity emerges",
        "latex": "\\boxed{\\,\\lim_{t\\to\\infty} v(t) = v_{\\text{term}} = \\dfrac{mg}{b}\\,}",
        "prose": "The memorized terminal velocity is the long-time limit of the solution — and SymPy proves the limit.",
        "emphasis": true
      }
    ]
  },
  "proof": {
    "kind": "governing",
    "heading": "The closed form provably solves the equation of motion — and terminal velocity falls out.",
    "checked_by": "sympy",
    "holds": true,
    "detail": "back-substitute $v(t)$ into $v' = g - v/\\tau$; check the initial condition; check $dx/dt = v$; check $\\lim v = g\\tau$",
    "checks": [
      {
        "key": "solves_eom",
        "claim": "The closed form solves the equation of motion $v' = g - v/\\tau$.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "ic_velocity",
        "claim": "It matches the initial velocity $v(0) = v_0$.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "x_is_integral_of_v",
        "claim": "Position is the integral of velocity ($dx/dt = v$).",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "terminal_limit",
        "claim": "The terminal velocity falls out: $v \\to g\\tau = mg/b$ as $t \\to \\infty$.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      }
    ]
  },
  "units_check": {
    "checked_by": "sympy",
    "holds": true
  },
